    keyTakeaways: ["Gross margin = (Revenue - Cost of Goods Sold) \u00f7 Revenue \u00d7 100.", "It tells you how efficiently you convert sales into profit before overheads.", "UK eCommerce averages 40\u201355% gross margin; below 30% is usually a red flag."],
    content: [
      { heading: "The formula", body: "Gross margin is calculated as: (Revenue minus Cost of Goods Sold) divided by Revenue, expressed as a percentage. If you sell a product for \u00a3100 and it costs you \u00a360 to make or buy, your gross margin is 40%. That \u00a340 must cover your rent, staff, marketing, and everything else \u2014 and leave something as profit." },
      { heading: "What counts as cost of goods sold?", body: "COGS includes the direct costs of producing or purchasing what you sell: product cost, packaging, direct labour, inbound freight, import duties. It does not include marketing, rent, salaries for non-production staff, or software. Getting COGS right is essential \u2014 underestimating it inflates your apparent margin." },
      { heading: "Why gross margin matters more than revenue", body: "Two businesses can have the same revenue and very different futures. A \u00a3500,000 revenue business at 60% gross margin has \u00a3300,000 to cover overheads. At 20% gross margin, it has \u00a3100,000 \u2014 and is likely loss-making once overheads are included. Gross margin determines how much room you have to grow." },
      { heading: "How to improve it", body: "Raise prices (if the market allows), reduce supplier costs (negotiate, consolidate, switch), improve product mix (sell more high-margin products), and reduce waste and returns. Even a 3\u20135 percentage point improvement in gross margin can transform a business's profitability." },
    ],
    relatedSlugs: ["what-is-net-profit-margin", "what-is-contribution-margin", "what-is-break-even-point"],
