    content: [
      { heading: "The formula", body: "Click-through rate is clicks divided by impressions, expressed as a percentage. If your ad is shown 10,000 times and clicked 150 times, CTR is 1.5%. It measures how compelling your creative, copy, and targeting are \u2014 how effectively your message motivates the people who see it to take the next step." },
      { heading: "CTR benchmarks by channel", body: "Email marketing: 2\u20135% CTR is typical, with well-segmented campaigns achieving higher. Google Search: 3\u201310% CTR for branded terms, 1\u20135% for non-branded. Google Display: 0.1\u20130.5% is typical (most display is ignored). Facebook/Instagram feed ads: 0.5\u20131.5%. LinkedIn: 0.2\u20130.5%. These vary significantly by industry, offer, and targeting quality \u2014 use them as starting points, not absolutes." },
      { heading: "High CTR, low conversion \u2014 the disconnect", body: "A high CTR means your ad is compelling. A low conversion rate after click means your landing page is failing. This disconnect \u2014 strong creative, weak landing experience \u2014 is common. The fix is landing page optimisation: message match between ad and page, clear value proposition, streamlined path to purchase, and social proof at the right moment." },
      { heading: "Using CTR to test creative", body: "CTR is one of the fastest metrics to respond to creative changes, making it useful for A/B testing. Test headline vs headline, image vs image, offer vs offer. Higher CTR on a variant indicates stronger messaging resonance with the audience. Scale the winner and continue testing against the control." },
    ],
