    description: "SEO is the practice of improving your website's visibility in organic search results. The highest-value long-term marketing investment for most businesses.",
    category: "Marketing Intelligence",
    categorySlug: "marketing-intelligence",
    difficulty: "Beginner",
    readTime: 5,
    keywords: ["SEO", "search engine optimisation", "organic search", "Google ranking", "content marketing"],
    keyTakeaways: [
      "SEO drives visitors to your website from unpaid (organic) search results",
      "The three pillars are technical SEO, on-page content, and backlinks",
      "SEO traffic has near-zero marginal cost — the ROI compounds over time",
      "Results take 3-12 months — SEO requires patience and consistency",
    ],
    content: [
      { heading: "What SEO is", body: "Search Engine Optimisation (SEO) is the practice of improving your website's content, structure, and authority so that search engines rank it higher in organic (unpaid) search results. When someone searches for a product, service, or question you can answer, appearing on the first page of Google is one of the most valuable positions in digital marketing." },
      { heading: "The three pillars of SEO", body: "Technical SEO ensures search engines can crawl, index, and understand your website: fast page loading, mobile responsiveness, clean URL structure, and an XML sitemap. On-page SEO is about your content: keyword research to understand what your audience searches for, and creating content that answers those searches better than competitors. Off-page SEO is about authority: the quality and quantity of reputable websites linking to yours." },
      { heading: "Keyword research", body: "Keyword research identifies what search queries your target audience uses, how many searches they generate monthly (search volume), and how difficult it is to rank for each term. Tools like Ahrefs, SEMrush, and Google Keyword Planner provide this data. Find keywords with meaningful volume that are achievable given your current domain authority, and create content that matches the intent behind those searches." },
      { heading: "Why SEO has the best long-term ROI", body: "Unlike paid advertising, where visibility stops when you stop spending, SEO traffic compounds. A well-written article that ranks on page one of Google today may still generate traffic three years from now with minimal maintenance. Businesses that invest consistently in SEO over 5+ years typically have significantly lower customer acquisition costs than those reliant on paid channels." },
      { heading: "Managing expectations", body: "SEO is slow. New websites and content typically take 3-12 months to begin ranking meaningfully for competitive terms. The key is to start early, be consistent, and measure progress through leading indicators (keyword rankings, organic traffic) rather than waiting for revenue attribution. Businesses that wait until they urgently need SEO results before starting always wish they had started earlier." },
    ],
    relatedSlugs: ["what-is-content-to-conversion", "what-is-demand-signal", "what-is-marketing-attribution"],
