    slug: "what-is-ebitda-forecasting",
    title: "What Is EBITDA Forecasting?",
    description: "EBITDA forecasting projects your operating earnings before interest, tax, and non-cash charges — the metric investors and lenders focus on when valuing your business.",
    category: "Financial Forecasting",
    categorySlug: "financial-forecasting",
    difficulty: "Intermediate",
    readTime: 6,
    keywords: ["EBITDA", "EBITDA forecasting", "operating profit", "business valuation", "SME finance"],
    keyTakeaways: [
      "EBITDA stands for Earnings Before Interest, Tax, Depreciation, and Amortisation.",
      "It is a widely used proxy for operating cash generation and business valuation.",
      "Forecasting EBITDA helps SMEs set performance targets aligned with investor and lender expectations.",
      "EBITDA is not a cash flow measure — it ignores CapEx, working capital, and debt service.",
    ],
    content: [
      { heading: "What EBITDA is and why it matters", body: "EBITDA stands for Earnings Before Interest, Tax, Depreciation, and Amortisation. It represents the operating profit of a business before accounting for financing costs (interest), tax charges, and non-cash accounting charges (depreciation and amortisation). EBITDA is widely used in business valuation — acquisition multiples are frequently expressed as a multiple of EBITDA — and by lenders as a measure of debt-service capacity. For SME owners considering a sale, refinancing, or seeking growth capital, forecasting EBITDA is essential because it is often the metric investors and lenders will focus on first." },
      { heading: "How to build an EBITDA forecast", body: "An EBITDA forecast starts with a revenue forecast, then subtracts the cost of goods sold to arrive at gross profit. Operating expenses — salaries, marketing, rent, software, and all other overhead costs except depreciation and amortisation — are then deducted to arrive at EBITDA. The key is to exclude depreciation and amortisation from the cost forecast, since these are non-cash charges that are added back in the EBITDA calculation. A common mistake is to include depreciation in the operating cost line and then fail to add it back, resulting in an understated EBITDA figure." },
      { heading: "EBITDA margin as a performance benchmark", body: "EBITDA margin — EBITDA as a percentage of revenue — is the metric most often used to benchmark operating efficiency against industry peers. A 20% EBITDA margin means that for every £100 of revenue, £20 is available to service debt, pay tax, fund capital investment, and ultimately return to shareholders. Industry benchmarks vary significantly: SaaS businesses may target 20–30% EBITDA margins at scale; logistics and retail businesses typically operate at 5–10%. Knowing your industry benchmark gives you a target to build your forecast around and a context for explaining your numbers to external stakeholders." },
      { heading: "The limitations of EBITDA", body: "EBITDA is a useful but imperfect metric, and SME owners should understand its limitations. It is not a cash flow measure: it ignores capital expenditure (the cash cost of replacing and upgrading assets), changes in working capital (the cash tied up in debtors and inventory), and debt repayment. A business can have strong EBITDA but a weak cash position if it has high CapEx requirements or long debtor collection cycles. Always pair an EBITDA forecast with a cash flow forecast to get the complete picture. Similarly, EBITDA can be manipulated by changing accounting treatment of capitalised costs, so scrutinise the definitions carefully when comparing your numbers to external benchmarks." },
    ],
    relatedSlugs: ["what-is-financial-modelling", "what-is-contribution-margin-analysis", "what-is-run-rate", "what-is-capex-vs-opex"],
